docs.abstract: The retail executive, Angela Ahrendts, says that the Phantom, a non-Apple wireless speaker which starts at $1,990, will receive prominent display treatment.
docs.snippet: The retail executive, Angela Ahrendts, says that the Phantom, a non-Apple wireless speaker which starts at $1,990, will receive prominent display treatment.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Angela Ahrendts, Apple’s senior vice president for retail, got a private demonstration of the fancy wireless speaker, the Phantom, and its sound quality seven weeks ago. On the spot, she said she wanted the space-pod-like device, which starts at $1,990, to be sold in Apple’s retail stores.

headline.main: Apple Executive Seeks a Touch of Chic at Retail Stores
headline.print_headline: A New Executive Pushes Apple Stores Into an Even Higher End

docs.abstract: James B. Comey told senators that one of the attackers in a recent shooting in Garland, Tex., “exchanged 109 messages with an overseas terrorist” that investigators could not read.
docs.snippet: James B. Comey told senators that one of the attackers in a recent shooting in Garland, Tex., “exchanged 109 messages with an overseas terrorist” that investigators could not read.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The F.B.I. director, James B. Comey, said Wednesday that investigators could not read more than 100 text messages exchanged by one of the attackers in a shooting this year in Garland, Tex., because they were encrypted, adding fuel to law enforcement agencies’ contention that they need a way to circumvent commercially available encryption technology.

headline.main: F.B.I. Chief Says Texas Gunman Used Encryption to Text Overseas Terrorist
headline.print_headline: F.B.I. Chief Says Gunman Used Encryption to Text Terrorist

docs.abstract: The composer Daniel Pemberton discusses how the soundtrack came together for the Danny Boyle film “Steve Jobs.”
docs.snippet: The composer Daniel Pemberton discusses how the soundtrack came together for the Danny Boyle film “Steve Jobs.”
docs.lead_paragraph: What should the soundtrack be to the life of a tech visionary? In the Danny Boyle film “Steve Jobs,” there is no simple answer. The film captures the life of the co-founder of Apple in an unusual way, focusing on three product launches during Mr. Jobs’s career, in 1984, 1989 and 1998. We stay behind the scenes at these launches, with the tensions and emotional beats of the movie played out in hallways and dressing rooms. And the score, by Daniel Pemberton, aims to capture Mr. Jobs’s mood as well as set up the stakes of his involvement with Apple and beyond.
